The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: Extracted preferences and dislikes (from my self‑introduction)
- Preferences: immediacy and cohesion of a single performance; warm analogue tone; guitar‑forward but organic band interplay; spacious mixes; generous dynamic range; emotive, intimate lead vocals that reward start‑to‑finish listening; cohesive sequencing that supports uninterrupted CD listening. I also appreciate polished, warm mid‑era studio production and clear lead vocal presence in piano‑led singer‑songwriter material.
- Dislikes: sprawling compilations/retrospectives; densely layered, band‑centric records that bury the lead in multi‑vocal harmonies or sprawling arrangements; reverb‑heavy, ethereal textures or murky, cluttered production; heavily processed production that undermines a unified single‑session listening experience.
Evaluation and rationale
- Candidate 2 (Classic rock/AOR live‑style album) matches the core of my stated preferences almost verbatim: it is captured as a single, well‑recorded performance (immediacy/cohesion), features warm analogue tone, is guitar‑forward with minimal overdubs and organic band interplay, has spacious mixes, generous dynamics and emotive, intimate lead vocals, and is sequenced to reward uninterrupted CD listening. Those are exactly the attributes I said I favor, so this CD will deliver the single‑session feel, vocal intimacy and dynamic contrasts I seek.
- Candidate 1 (Classic Rock/AOR anthology) does have some attractive features — album‑oriented sequencing, guitar‑driven arrangements, longer tracks and deeper cuts that reward focused listening and reveal nuances over repeats. However, it is explicitly an anthology, which fits the “sprawling compilation/retrospective” category I dislike. An anthology by definition collects material from different sessions, producers and eras, so it is unlikely to present the unified, single‑performance sonic identity, consistent analogue warmth and cohesive, intimate vocal presentation I prioritize. The “varied textures” and “dynamic production details” mentioned are strengths in another context, but here they signal unevenness across tracks and potential inclusion of denser or more produced arrangements that could dilute vocal immediacy.
Conclusion
Because my primary criteria emphasize a single, well‑captured performance with analogue warmth, minimal overdubs, guitar‑forward but organic interplay, spacious mixes and intimate lead vocals — and because I explicitly dislike sprawling compilations and inconsistent, multi‑session productions — the Classic rock/AOR live‑style album is the clear fit. The anthology format of Candidate 1 risks the very fragmentation and production variance that would undermine the focused, start‑to‑finish CD listening experience I seek, so I reject it in favor of Candidate 2.

