- Immediate 17‑11‑70: close‑mic’d, weathered vocal with breath and dynamics and transient‑preserving mastering with generous headroom (excellent for vocal micro‑detail and immediacy); punchy drums and tight elastic bass and intimate small‑room ambience (good for in‑the‑room feel). However, it explicitly features jangly midrange guitars and is a live set with sparse arrangements and small‑room ambience — the jangly midrange guitars conflict with my dislike of mid‑forward riffy guitars, and a live small‑room ambience can introduce more room character that risks moving away from the low‑reverb, piano/voice intimacy I prize. Also, the live set doesn’t promise the same career‑spanning, carefully sequenced, collector‑grade packaging the anthology offers.
Decision rationale
The Chronological anthology best aligns with the majority of my stated priorities: analogue warmth and preserved micro‑dynamics, low compression and generous headroom, guitars intentionally de‑emphasized in the midrange (avoiding the exact mid‑forward guitar issue I dislike), and punchy/tight rhythm support. Crucially, it also promises career‑spanning, artist‑curated sequencing and tasteful rarities — matching my desire for cohesive album flow and collector‑grade presentation. Immediate 17‑11‑70 has many virtues (intimate, close‑mic’d vocals and excellent dynamics) but its jangly midrange guitars and live small‑room coloration make it less ideal for my piano/voice‑first tastes and my aversion to mid‑forward guitar textures. For those reasons I select the Chronological anthology.

